<DocsLayout title="Tool as Capability" section="Concepts"><Hero eyebrow="Concept 05" title="Tool is capability." lede="An agent should understand what a business capability does—not the protocol details used to implement it." reading="8 min" difficulty="Core" prerequisite="Decision & Execution" />
<Question>Can the tool change its internal API without changing the agent?</Question>
<Diagram title="Hide transport behind capability" chart={chart} />
<Principle title="Describe intent, validate action."><p>A good tool exposes a narrow business verb, typed input, explicit side effects, permission checks, and a concise observation.</p></Principle>
<CaseBlock title="SearchBid is stable even when the portal changes."><p>The agent calls SearchBid. The adapter may use REST today and a vendor SDK tomorrow. The agent contract remains unchanged.</p></CaseBlock>
<Decision question="Why not expose raw SQL or generic HTTP?" answer="Generic tools enlarge the attack surface and force the model to understand infrastructure rather than business intent." alternative="No shell tool. No arbitrary SQL. No generic write endpoint." />
<Takeaway>A tool should reveal the business capability and hide the implementation.</Takeaway></DocsLayout>